<br>
For the former, take the following example:  If you Naltron everyone in the group but only one or two of the members is getting hit such that you're dropping a heal on them occasionally, you've essentially wasted a bunch of pp and mana recovery downtime for nothing.  However, if you've got a tank who's continuously getting clocked and you're chealing him/her pretty often, then dropping a Naltron on them makes your cheals much more efficient.  Efficient heals = less mana recovery time = less downtime = happy, fun night in EQ <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   In cases where you're not sure who's going to be taking damage and at what rate, start out with a Pinzarn on everyone, and move to Naltron when you've got a better feel for who's getting hit the most.  Sometimes, you find that you don't need to bother with Symbol at all.  I know I've been on a ton of Fear/Hate raids where I haven't had to cast Symbol the entire raid.<br>
<br>
Also, don't forget your AC buffs; personally, I think they're often underrated.  Yes, they're mana hogs, but they really seem to cut down the healing load on tanks who are in continual contact with the mobs.  To minimize downtime, I always do AC buffs two members at a time (i.e. AC buff two tanks, when you're back to full mana AC buff the next two tanks, etc.)  That way, I can stay at &quot;good-to-go&quot; mana the entire time, and everyone's not waiting for me to med up.<br>
<br>
As far as the latter, ask yourself the following question:  &quot;Is there a member (or two) of the group who, if he/she dies, means the death of all of us?&quot;  Typically, that means you're in a pretty tough area (e.g. a single group of early 50's in Chardok, or, say, the AoF room in CT at earlier levels), and more than likely, that person is the enchanter.  In cases like these, it seems pretty practical to keep your best symbol buff on the high-risk person.<br>
<br>
